            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I've now successfully written a hack that overwrites `uv.spawn`, `uv.new_pipe`, and `vim.fn.executable` so I can provide my own implementation. See [distant.lsp.start_client](https://github.com/chipsenkbeil/distant.nvim/blob/aca976c59b2e020d0d9e4d89b9e8c99eb36a21ae/lua/distant/lsp.lua#L208).\r\n\r\nFor `uv.spawn`, I return a table that implements:\r\n* is_closing\r\n* close\r\n* kill\r\n\r\nFor `uv.new_pipe`, I return a table that implements:\r\n* close\r\n* read_start\r\n* write\r\n\r\nFor `vim.fn.executable`, I temporarily set it to return 1 at all times as there is a check within the `vim.lsp.rpc.start` function to ensure that command is executable. This should instead be up to the user-defined spawner to validate instead of neovim.\r\n\r\nI have to do some extra trickery for the pipes as I need to update them when they are passed to `uv.spawn` in order for them to be functional.\r\n\r\nIdeally, if we wrote an alternative way to start a client, creating the stdin, stdout, and stderr pipes would be handled by the user and not something done explicitly by neovim. That way, the user just needs to return tables that have the above methods on them, rather than having to overwrite `uv.new_pipe` as well.\r\n\r\n@mjlbach @tjdevries thoughts on this one? @mfussenegger, skimming through your code above, did you implement your own session handling as opposed to using neovim's rpc management?",
