            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@mjlbach distant doesn't necessarily need another method of communication from the above. It's a lua module that - through the hack described above - returns a matching handle and pipes. While distant communicates over TCP to a remote server, the actual LSP communication is done over stdio. Distant relays stdin, stdout, and stderr between the LSP and neovim, but to neovim it would look like it is talking to a local process over stdin. At least, that's how it works today.\r\n\r\nThis way, there's no dependence on a remote LSP server supporting TCP itself. Distant takes care of all of that for you.\r\n\r\n<img width=\"574\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2481802/137681931-525cbc6e-ab1b-42d8-b2e6-1bc11fc62a1b.png\">\r\n",
